// The `prelude.mcp` sub-module: MCP in both directions, as ordinary agent values. Outbound, `provide`
// plugs any MCP server's tools into a program for the extent of a scope; inbound, `serve` publishes a
// program's own agents AS an MCP server for the extent of a subscriber. Both route to the runtime's
// `mcp` reactor (an in-runtime MCP client / server, like `http.fetch`'s in-runtime fetch — no FFI
// sidecar, nothing for the user to install).
//
// Outbound, the whole integration is one line — the tools live for the extent of the `use` block, and
// you pick how the server authenticates with the `auth` sum:
//
//   let tools : mcp.toolbox["https://..."] = use mcp.provide(url = "https://...", auth = mcp.headers(values = record.empty()))
//   let tools : mcp.toolbox["https://..."] = use mcp.provide(url = "https://...", auth = mcp.oauth(name = "github"))
//
// `headers` covers anonymous access (an empty record), bearer keys and any custom scheme uniformly:
// the given headers ride on every request. `oauth` names an OAuth credential stored server-side; the
// runtime injects (and refreshes) its tokens itself, so no token material appears in the program. When
// the named credential is missing — or dies beyond what a refresh can fix, even mid-run — the program
// does not fail: the run PAUSES on a user-facing `prelude.oauth.authorize` escalation, the admin console
// and CLI render it as an OAuth authorization request, and completing the browser flow resumes the run
// right where it stopped.
//
// THE SCOPE STORY. A tool is a live capability, not a value that may outlive its connection: it exists
// only WHILE its `provide` is running. `provide` is a scoped provider (the ST-monad `runST` shape) — it
// lists the server, hands the continuation a `toolbox[URL]`, and DISCHARGES the `scope[URL]` marker from
// its own result row. A tool carries `scope[URL]` in its effect row (`tool[URL]` below), so a call to it
// is only well-typed inside a row that still carries that scope — which only `provide`'s continuation
// does. The tools therefore cannot escape their `provide`: return one and the `scope[URL]` it drags along
// has nowhere to be discharged, a type error. `scope[URL]` is a phantom marker (it names no operation, is
// never performed and never handled, and vanishes at lowering); its URL parameter is phantom too, so it
// is COVARIANT in a row — `scope["x"]` fits a `scope[string]` context but never `scope["y"]`.
//
// THE COVARIANCE CONSEQUENCE. A literal `url` gives per-URL scoping: `provide(url = "https://a")` mints
// `scope["https://a"]`, and a tool tagged `scope["https://a"]` fits only a context carrying that exact
// scope. A dynamic (non-literal) `url` degrades to `scope[string]` — the widest scope — and by covariance
// a `scope[string]` context can run a tool of ANY concrete URL. That hole (a `string`-scoped continuation
// that smuggles in a foreign-URL tool) is the one thing the type system cannot rule out, so the runtime
// backstops it: every scope is a runtime identity, and a tool call carrying a scope its `provide` has
// already closed is rejected with a typed `server_error` naming the closed scope. The type system prevents
// everything else; this catches only the dynamic-URL covariance case.
//
// A tool IS an agent: the runtime mints one agent value per server tool, carrying the server-declared
// name / description / input schema (and output schema when the server declares one) —
// `reflection.get_metadata` reads them (that is what an AI loop advertises), and a call is validated
// against that schema before anything runs (a bad argument throws `reflection.call_error` without the
// server ever being contacted). Each minted tool carries its server DESCRIPTOR (the url + auth it was
// listed with) and its scope identity; the runtime (re)connects lazily per descriptor — reusing a live
// connection across calls, reconnecting transparently after a failure or a runtime restart, and closing it
// when the last `provide` on that descriptor returns. A header value may be a secret (`string of private`);
// it stays private inside the tool value (sealed at rest, redacted at user-facing boundaries) and is
// revealed only to the server itself. An `oauth` credential's NAME is not a secret — the tokens it names
// never enter the program.
//
// Inbound, `serve` mirrors `webhook.inbound`: the runtime mints a fresh, unguessable capability URL and
// serves the given record's agents as MCP tools there for exactly as long as @subscriber@ runs. The URL
// IS the key — possession grants access, nothing else does (the endpoint lives outside the
// bearer-authenticated API surface, and the token is generated fresh per call); when the subscriber
// returns, or the run is cancelled, the URL deactivates. A served agent is self-contained (its effects
// are handled, or are at most `io` and this module's throws), so a user's own typed agents fit as tools
// without ceremony. A served tool that FAILS is not answered per-call: an unhandled throw or panic proxies
// UP like any escalation and cancels the whole endpoint (the run fails unless a handler above @subscriber@
// catches it) — one buggy tool drops the server, so for per-request resilience wrap the tool's body in a
// handler that turns a failure into a value it returns.

@"The MCP server rejected a listing or a tool call, or the transport failed (the server-reported or
transport message). Also raised as the scope backstop: a tool called after its `provide` returned reports
its closed scope this way. Catch it to control retry — a retried call reconnects."
data server_error(message: string)

@"The server rejected the `headers` key material. Retrying with the same material does not help: a
human must fix the key the program supplies. Never raised on the `oauth` path — an unusable `oauth`
credential pauses the run on an authorization escalation instead of failing it. Distinct from
`server_error` so a program can catch the two differently."
data auth_error(message: string)

@"Header-based access: @values@ ride on every request to the server (each value may be a secret,
such as a bearer key). Anonymous access is `headers(values = record.empty())`."
data headers(@"The headers sent on every request, by name; a value may be a secret." values: record[string of private])

@"A named OAuth credential, stored server-side. The runtime injects and refreshes its tokens itself;
the name is not a secret. While the name has no usable credential, any use pauses the run on a
`prelude.oauth.authorize` escalation — answering it (the runtime-hosted browser flow) establishes the
credential and resumes the run."
data oauth(@"The stored credential's registered name; not a secret." name: string)

// How `provide` authenticates with the server: explicit headers, or a named OAuth credential.
type auth = headers | oauth

@"A pure scope capability, keyed by its server URL: carried in a tool's effect row, never performable,
never handleable. `provide` mints it for its continuation's row and discharges it from its own, so a
tool tagged `scope[URL]` cannot outlive the `provide` that introduced it. Its URL is phantom (covariant):
`scope[\"x\"]` fits a `scope[string]` row, never a `scope[\"y\"]` one."
effect scope[URL]

// One server tool, as an ordinary agent value, gated by its provide scope. (Type synonyms take no docs.)
type tool[URL] = agent never -> unknown with io | scope[URL] | prelude.throw[server_error | auth_error]

// A server's tools, keyed by tool name — call one by key, or hand `record.values(target = ...)` (the
// flat array of tools) to an AI loop wholesale. `URL` is the scope the tools are gated by.
type toolbox[URL] = record[tool[URL]]

@"Plug an MCP server's tools into a program for the extent of @continuation@, as a scoped provider —
the `use mcp.provide(url = ..., auth = ...)` form. The runtime lists the server (a missing or dead
`oauth` credential pauses on an authorization escalation and retries once answered; rejected `headers`
material throws `auth_error`; a rejected listing throws `server_error`), hands @continuation@
a `toolbox[URL]` of one runtime-minted agent per tool (each carrying the server signature — for
`reflection.get_metadata` and call-site validation — and the descriptor it was listed with), and settles
with the continuation's result. `scope[URL]` rides the continuation's row (that is what a tool call
raises) and is DISCHARGED from `provide`'s own row, so a tool cannot escape the block: the scope closes
when @continuation@ returns (or the run is cancelled), and a stray later call is rejected as a typed
`server_error`. A literal @url@ binds `URL` to that string's singleton (per-URL scoping); a dynamic @url@
degrades `URL` to `string` (the widest scope — see the module header)."
external agent provide[literal URL, R, effect E](
  @"The MCP server's endpoint URL (streamable HTTP, with SSE fallback)." url: URL,
  @"How the runtime authenticates with the server: `headers(...)` or `oauth(...)`." auth: auth,
  @"The scope body (bound by `use`): receives the toolbox, and the tools are callable exactly while it runs." continuation: agent (value: toolbox[URL]) -> R with E | scope[URL],
) -> R with E from "mcp"

@"Call one tool on an MCP server directly — the static counterpart of `provide`, with no listing and no
minted agent value. The seam the binding modules `katari mcp pull` generates are built on: @tool@ is the
server-declared tool name, @arguments@ its arguments object as a literal `json` tree (a typed wrapper
builds it with `json.encode` per parameter). The result is DECODED against @T@ inside the runtime, exactly
as `json.decode[T]` decodes the server's reply: a tool's `structuredContent` is read as @T@'s wire form
(so a `$ref` handle object reconstructs a REAL `file` value, and records / arrays / scalars land as
values), a plain-text reply decodes only into a string-shaped @T@, and a schema mismatch throws
`decode_error`. Instantiate @T@ with `json.json` to keep the reply as a raw `json` tree instead (the
codegen's choice when no `outputSchema` maps): a `$ref` then stays an inert object inside the tree, which
`json.decode` with a `file`-typed shape can still reconstruct later. @T@ appears only in the result, so it
is never inferable — instantiate it explicitly; the literal @url@ generic is inferred from the argument,
so a caller writes both arguments to `[...]`, `mcp.call[url_literal, T](url = url_literal, ...)`. Nothing
validates @arguments@ before the server does (unlike a minted tool) — a rejected call throws
`server_error`. Scope-gated the same way as a minted tool (`scope[URL]` on its row, a literal @url@
binding it per-URL): a generated binding calls this only inside a `provide` scope over the same
descriptor, and the runtime rejects a call with no live scope for that descriptor as a typed
`server_error`."
external agent call[literal URL, T](
  @"The MCP server's endpoint URL (the same descriptor the surrounding `provide` scope was opened with)." url: URL,
  @"How the runtime authenticates with the server: `headers(...)` or `oauth(...)`." auth: auth,
  @"The server-declared tool name." tool: string,
  @"The tool's arguments object, as a literal `json` tree; only the server validates it." arguments: json.json,
) -> T with scope[URL] | prelude.throw[server_error | auth_error | json.decode_error] from "mcp"

@"Publish @tools@ as a live MCP server for the extent of @subscriber@. The runtime mints a fresh,
unguessable capability URL and serves the record's agents as MCP tools there — each record key is
the published tool name, each agent's declared signature the tool's advertised schema. The URL is
the key: possession grants access, nobody without it can call in. @subscriber@ receives the URL,
hands it to whoever should connect (an AI session, a teammate's MCP client), and stays alive while
calls should be served; when it returns the URL deactivates and its result becomes `serve`'s
result. Cancelling the run cancels @subscriber@ and deactivates the URL the same way. The
subscriber's effects flow to the caller's handlers unchanged; the served agents are self-contained
(their effects are handled, or are at most `io` and this module's throws), so any agent fits once its
own effects are handled. A served tool that throws or panics with no handler of its own cancels the
whole endpoint (its failure proxies up and fails the run unless caught above @subscriber@) — wrap a
tool's body in a handler for per-request resilience."
external agent serve[R, effect E](
  @"The agents to publish, keyed by the tool name each is published under." tools: toolbox[string],
  @"The endpoint's owner: receives the capability URL, and the server serves exactly while it runs." subscriber: agent (url: string) -> R with E,
) -> R with E from "mcp"
